The second argument to `mergeMap` is the concurrency cap. `concatMap` would serialise (1-at-a-time); `switchMap` would cancel the previous upload when a new file arrives — neither is what a batch uploader wants.

```ts
import { Observable, from } from 'rxjs';
import { mergeMap } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface UploadJob {
  id: string;
  blob: Blob;
}

interface UploadResult {
  id: string;
  url: string;
}

declare function uploadOne$(job: UploadJob): Observable<UploadResult>;

export function uploadQueue(
  jobs: ReadonlyArray<UploadJob>
): Observable<UploadResult> {
  return from(jobs).pipe(
    mergeMap((job: UploadJob) => uploadOne$(job), 4)
  );
}
```

At most four uploads run in parallel; the rest queue until a slot frees up.

Use `mergeMap(project, concurrency)`. The second positional argument caps the in-flight inner subscriptions.

```ts
import { Observable, from } from 'rxjs';
import { mergeMap } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface FetchTask {
  url: string;
}

interface FetchOutcome {
  url: string;
  status: number;
}

declare function httpGet$(url: string): Observable<FetchOutcome>;

export function runQueue(
  tasks: ReadonlyArray<FetchTask>
): Observable<FetchOutcome> {
  return from(tasks).pipe(
    mergeMap((t: FetchTask) => httpGet$(t.url), 3)
  );
}
```

Results arrive interleaved in whatever order the inner calls complete — that's the usual `mergeMap` property. Use `concatMap` if you need strict ordering instead.

```ts
import { Observable, from } from 'rxjs';
import { mergeMap } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface PrefetchRequest {
  src: string;
  priority: 'high' | 'low';
}

interface PrefetchResult {
  src: string;
  bytes: number;
  fromCache: boolean;
}

declare function fetchImage$(req: PrefetchRequest): Observable<PrefetchResult>;

// Cap at 6 concurrent fetches so we don't saturate the browser's
// per-origin HTTP connection limit.
export function prefetchImages(
  requests: ReadonlyArray<PrefetchRequest>
): Observable<PrefetchResult> {
  return from(requests).pipe(
    mergeMap((r: PrefetchRequest) => fetchImage$(r), 6)
  );
}
```

The numeric cap is what makes `mergeMap` the right tool here — plain `mergeMap(fn)` (no limit) would kick off every fetch at once.

```ts
import { Observable, from } from 'rxjs';
import { mergeMap } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface EmailJob {
  to: string;
  subject: string;
  body: string;
}

interface SendReceipt {
  to: string;
  messageId: string;
}

declare function sendEmail$(job: EmailJob): Observable<SendReceipt>;

export function emailWorker(
  outbox: ReadonlyArray<EmailJob>
): Observable<SendReceipt> {
  return from(outbox).pipe(
    // SMTP providers throttle per-connection; keep 5 sends in flight.
    mergeMap((job: EmailJob) => sendEmail$(job), 5)
  );
}
```

`mergeMap` with a concurrency limit is the go-to for bounded parallelism: `concatMap` would be too slow (serial), `switchMap` would cancel the previous send — wrong semantics for a worker.

`mergeMap(project, concurrency)` subscribes to inner observables as outer values arrive, but only keeps up to `concurrency` of them running. When an inner completes, the next queued outer value gets projected. This gives you parallelism without unbounded fan-out.

```ts
import { Observable, from } from 'rxjs';
import { mergeMap } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface ThumbnailJob {
  sourceUrl: string;
  width: number;
}

interface ThumbnailResult {
  sourceUrl: string;
  thumbUrl: string;
}

declare function makeThumbnail$(job: ThumbnailJob): Observable<ThumbnailResult>;

export function thumbnailQueue(
  jobs: ReadonlyArray<ThumbnailJob>
): Observable<ThumbnailResult> {
  return from(jobs).pipe(
    mergeMap((j: ThumbnailJob) => makeThumbnail$(j), 2)
  );
}
```

Here we cap at 2 because the worker is CPU-bound and we want to leave headroom for the main thread.

With a concurrency cap of 1 you technically get `concatMap` semantics — but the intent here is "bounded parallelism whose current budget is 1", so expressing it via `mergeMap(_, 1)` keeps the operator choice honest.

```ts
import { Observable, from } from 'rxjs';
import { mergeMap } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface Migration {
  id: string;
  sql: string;
}

interface MigrationOutcome {
  id: string;
  appliedAt: number;
}

declare function applyMigration$(m: Migration): Observable<MigrationOutcome>;

export function runMigrations(
  pending: ReadonlyArray<Migration>
): Observable<MigrationOutcome> {
  return from(pending).pipe(
    mergeMap((m: Migration) => applyMigration$(m), 1)
  );
}
```

If ordering were the sole concern (no plan to raise the cap later), `concatMap` would be idiomatic.

```ts
import { Observable, from } from 'rxjs';
import { mergeMap } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface CrawlTask {
  url: string;
  depth: number;
}

interface CrawlResult {
  url: string;
  linksOut: ReadonlyArray<string>;
  bytes: number;
}

declare function crawlOne$(task: CrawlTask): Observable<CrawlResult>;

// Bounded parallelism: 8 pages in flight — polite but not glacial.
export function frontier(
  seed: ReadonlyArray<CrawlTask>
): Observable<CrawlResult> {
  return from(seed).pipe(
    mergeMap((task: CrawlTask) => crawlOne$(task), 8)
  );
}
```

`mergeMap` interleaves completed pages in arrival order. `switchMap` would abandon in-flight fetches whenever a new task appeared — catastrophic for a crawler.

RxJS has it built in — `mergeMap(project, concurrency)` IS the gate. No extra library needed.

```ts
import { Observable, from } from 'rxjs';
import { mergeMap } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface ApiCall {
  endpoint: string;
  payload: string;
}

interface ApiResult {
  endpoint: string;
  status: number;
}

declare function callApi$(c: ApiCall): Observable<ApiResult>;

export function limited(
  calls: ReadonlyArray<ApiCall>,
  limit: number
): Observable<ApiResult> {
  return from(calls).pipe(
    mergeMap((c: ApiCall) => callApi$(c), limit)
  );
}
```

Pass the gate size as a parameter if you want it runtime-configurable.

```ts
import { Observable, from } from 'rxjs';
import { mergeMap } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface DeleteKey {
  bucket: string;
  key: string;
}

interface DeleteAck {
  bucket: string;
  key: string;
  versionId: string | null;
}

declare function deleteObject$(k: DeleteKey): Observable<DeleteAck>;

export function bulkDelete(
  keys: ReadonlyArray<DeleteKey>
): Observable<DeleteAck> {
  return from(keys).pipe(
    // S3 handles burstiness well; 20 in flight is fine.
    mergeMap((k: DeleteKey) => deleteObject$(k), 20)
  );
}
```

Compare: `concatMap` would be far too slow for thousands of keys; `mergeMap` unbounded (no second arg) would fire all N requests at once and likely 503.

```ts
import { Observable, from } from 'rxjs';
import { mergeMap } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface BuildJob {
  repo: string;
  commit: string;
  targets: ReadonlyArray<string>;
}

interface BuildReport {
  repo: string;
  commit: string;
  durationMs: number;
  passed: boolean;
}

declare function runBuild$(job: BuildJob): Observable<BuildReport>;

export function dispatchBuilds(
  jobs: ReadonlyArray<BuildJob>,
  workerSlots: number
): Observable<BuildReport> {
  return from(jobs).pipe(
    mergeMap((job: BuildJob) => runBuild$(job), workerSlots)
  );
}
```

Reports stream back as each worker finishes — order is arrival-completion, not input order.

`mergeMap(_, concurrency)` — use the concurrency cap as your FD budget.

```ts
import { Observable, from } from 'rxjs';
import { mergeMap } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface DirTask {
  path: string;
}

interface ScanEntry {
  path: string;
  isDir: boolean;
  size: number;
}

declare function scanDir$(task: DirTask): Observable<ScanEntry>;

export function parallelScan(
  roots: ReadonlyArray<DirTask>
): Observable<ScanEntry> {
  return from(roots).pipe(
    // Stay well under typical ulimit -n (1024) per process.
    mergeMap((t: DirTask) => scanDir$(t), 64)
  );
}
```

```ts
import { Observable, from } from 'rxjs';
import { mergeMap } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface WebhookDelivery {
  deliveryId: string;
  url: string;
  payload: string;
  attempt: number;
}

interface DeliveryOutcome {
  deliveryId: string;
  status: 'ok' | 'retry' | 'dead';
}

declare function deliverWebhook$(
  d: WebhookDelivery
): Observable<DeliveryOutcome>;

export function dispatchWebhooks(
  queue: ReadonlyArray<WebhookDelivery>
): Observable<DeliveryOutcome> {
  return from(queue).pipe(
    mergeMap((d: WebhookDelivery) => deliverWebhook$(d), 10)
  );
}
```

`mergeMap` gives us interleaved completion (fast endpoints finish first); the cap of 10 keeps the downstream receivers from being hammered.

- `concatMap(fn)` — strictly one inner at a time, ordered. Slowest.
- `switchMap(fn)` — only the LATEST outer value matters; inflight inner gets cancelled.
- `mergeMap(fn, n)` — up to `n` inners in flight concurrently, interleaved results.

For bulk uploads you want `mergeMap` with a cap.

```ts
import { Observable, from } from 'rxjs';
import { mergeMap } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface LogChunk {
  sequence: number;
  bytes: Uint8Array;
}

interface UploadAck {
  sequence: number;
  serverTimeMs: number;
}

declare function uploadChunk$(c: LogChunk): Observable<UploadAck>;

export function uploadLogs(
  chunks: ReadonlyArray<LogChunk>
): Observable<UploadAck> {
  return from(chunks).pipe(
    mergeMap((c: LogChunk) => uploadChunk$(c), 4)
  );
}
```

```ts
import { Observable, from } from 'rxjs';
import { mergeMap } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface ProducerRecord {
  topic: string;
  key: string;
  value: string;
}

interface ProduceAck {
  topic: string;
  partition: number;
  offset: number;
}

declare function produce$(r: ProducerRecord): Observable<ProduceAck>;

export function produceBatch(
  records: ReadonlyArray<ProducerRecord>
): Observable<ProduceAck> {
  return from(records).pipe(
    // Kafka client already batches; 16 in-flight requests is a common default.
    mergeMap((r: ProducerRecord) => produce$(r), 16)
  );
}
```

`concatMap` would serialise — on a GPU-backed OCR worker that's wasteful because the backend can handle several pages in parallel. `mergeMap(_, N)` keeps N pages on the GPU at once without uncapped fan-out.

```ts
import { Observable, from } from 'rxjs';
import { mergeMap } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface OcrJob {
  documentId: string;
  pageIndex: number;
  imageUrl: string;
}

interface OcrResult {
  documentId: string;
  pageIndex: number;
  text: string;
  confidence: number;
}

declare function ocrPage$(j: OcrJob): Observable<OcrResult>;

export function ocrPipeline(
  pages: ReadonlyArray<OcrJob>
): Observable<OcrResult> {
  return from(pages).pipe(
    mergeMap((job: OcrJob) => ocrPage$(job), 3)
  );
}
```

```ts
import { Observable, from } from 'rxjs';
import { mergeMap } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface Address {
  raw: string;
}

interface Geocoded {
  raw: string;
  lat: number;
  lng: number;
  accuracy: 'rooftop' | 'street' | 'city';
}

declare function geocode$(a: Address): Observable<Geocoded>;

export function geocodeAll(
  addresses: ReadonlyArray<Address>
): Observable<Geocoded> {
  return from(addresses).pipe(
    // Provider caps us at 5 concurrent — respect it or get 429s.
    mergeMap((a: Address) => geocode$(a), 5)
  );
}
```

If the provider also caps requests-per-second, combine with `throttleTime` or a token-bucket operator upstream.

```ts
import { Observable, from } from 'rxjs';
import { mergeMap } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface HashTask {
  path: string;
  algorithm: 'sha256' | 'blake3';
}

interface HashResult {
  path: string;
  digest: string;
}

declare function hashFile$(t: HashTask): Observable<HashResult>;

export function hashAll(
  tasks: ReadonlyArray<HashTask>
): Observable<HashResult> {
  return from(tasks).pipe(
    mergeMap((t: HashTask) => hashFile$(t), 2)
  );
}
```

Two workers is a reasonable default on a 4-core machine for CPU-bound hashing — leaves headroom for the event loop.

```ts
import { Observable, from } from 'rxjs';
import { mergeMap } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface PushMessage {
  deviceToken: string;
  title: string;
  body: string;
  badge: number;
}

interface PushAck {
  deviceToken: string;
  accepted: boolean;
  providerId: string | null;
}

declare function sendPush$(m: PushMessage): Observable<PushAck>;

export function dispatchPush(
  messages: ReadonlyArray<PushMessage>
): Observable<PushAck> {
  return from(messages).pipe(
    mergeMap((m: PushMessage) => sendPush$(m), 12)
  );
}
```

Provider APNs/FCM accept parallel HTTP/2 streams, so 12 is comfortable but leaves headroom.

Without a cap, `mergeMap` subscribes to every inner observable as soon as its outer value arrives — for N outer values you get N simultaneous subscriptions. That's how you spawn 10,000 ffmpeg processes and wedge a box. Passing the concurrency argument caps the in-flight count so only N inners run; the rest queue inside the operator.

```ts
import { Observable, from } from 'rxjs';
import { mergeMap } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface TranscodeJob {
  srcUrl: string;
  targetBitrate: number;
  codec: 'h264' | 'av1';
}

interface TranscodeResult {
  srcUrl: string;
  outUrl: string;
  durationMs: number;
}

declare function transcode$(j: TranscodeJob): Observable<TranscodeResult>;

export function transcodeAll(
  jobs: ReadonlyArray<TranscodeJob>,
  cores: number
): Observable<TranscodeResult> {
  return from(jobs).pipe(
    mergeMap((j: TranscodeJob) => transcode$(j), cores)
  );
}
```

```ts
import { Observable, from } from 'rxjs';
import { mergeMap } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface ChargeIntent {
  customerId: string;
  amountCents: number;
  currency: 'usd' | 'eur';
}

interface ChargeOutcome {
  customerId: string;
  chargeId: string;
  status: 'succeeded' | 'requires_action' | 'failed';
}

declare function chargeCard$(i: ChargeIntent): Observable<ChargeOutcome>;

export function runCharges(
  intents: ReadonlyArray<ChargeIntent>
): Observable<ChargeOutcome> {
  return from(intents).pipe(
    // Payment APIs typically rate-limit hard; 4 in flight is safe.
    mergeMap((i: ChargeIntent) => chargeCard$(i), 4)
  );
}
```

`mergeMap` with cap is the right primitive: `concatMap` would be too slow for a batch, `switchMap` would cancel pending charges — catastrophic for money.

`Subject<T>` has no initial value and does not replay — a subscriber only sees values emitted AFTER it subscribes. `BehaviorSubject<T>` requires an initial value at construction, exposes `.getValue()` for synchronous reads, and immediately emits the current value to any new subscriber.

```ts
import { BehaviorSubject, Subject } from 'rxjs';

interface SessionState {
  authed: boolean;
  username: string | null;
}

const initial: SessionState = { authed: false, username: null };

// Pre-seeded + replays the latest to late subscribers.
export const session$ = new BehaviorSubject<SessionState>(initial);

// No seed, no replay — late subscribers miss prior events.
export const sessionEvents$ = new Subject<SessionState>();

session$.next({ authed: true, username: 'ada' });
const snap: SessionState = session$.getValue(); // { authed: true, ... }
void snap;
```

Reach for `BehaviorSubject` when the stream represents state; use `Subject` for one-shot events.

```ts
import { BehaviorSubject, Observable } from 'rxjs';

interface FeatureFlags {
  readonly newCheckout: boolean;
  readonly betaSearch: boolean;
  readonly darkMode: boolean;
}

const initialFlags: FeatureFlags = {
  newCheckout: false,
  betaSearch: false,
  darkMode: false,
};

const _flags$ = new BehaviorSubject<FeatureFlags>(initialFlags);

export const flags$: Observable<FeatureFlags> = _flags$.asObservable();

export function updateFlags(patch: Partial<FeatureFlags>): void {
  _flags$.next({ ..._flags$.getValue(), ...patch });
}

export function currentFlags(): FeatureFlags {
  // One-shot sync read (e.g. bootstrap code). Inside streams, subscribe.
  return _flags$.getValue();
}
```

Exposing `.asObservable()` stops consumers from calling `.next` and mutating state from outside the store.

```ts
import { BehaviorSubject, Observable } from 'rxjs';

interface CartItem {
  sku: string;
  quantity: number;
  priceCents: number;
}

interface Cart {
  readonly items: ReadonlyArray<CartItem>;
  readonly totalCents: number;
}

const emptyCart: Cart = { items: [], totalCents: 0 };

const _cart$ = new BehaviorSubject<Cart>(emptyCart);

export const cart$: Observable<Cart> = _cart$.asObservable();

function recompute(items: ReadonlyArray<CartItem>): Cart {
  const totalCents = items.reduce(
    (acc, i) => acc + i.priceCents * i.quantity,
    0,
  );
  return { items, totalCents };
}

export function addItem(item: CartItem): void {
  const current = _cart$.getValue();
  _cart$.next(recompute([...current.items, item]));
}

export function snapshotCart(): Cart {
  return _cart$.getValue();
}
```

Late subscribers (e.g. a header widget that mounts after items were added) see the populated cart immediately — that's the `BehaviorSubject` contract.

Three differences to internalise:

1. `BehaviorSubject<T>(initial)` requires an initial value — it is never "empty".
2. New subscribers receive the latest value synchronously on subscription.
3. `.getValue()` returns the current value without subscribing.

`Subject` has none of those — it is purely a hot event bus.

```ts
import { BehaviorSubject, Observable } from 'rxjs';

type Theme = 'light' | 'dark' | 'system';

const _theme$ = new BehaviorSubject<Theme>('system');

export const theme$: Observable<Theme> = _theme$.asObservable();

export function setTheme(next: Theme): void {
  _theme$.next(next);
}

export function currentTheme(): Theme {
  return _theme$.getValue();
}
```

A toolbar that mounts mid-session immediately paints with the right theme — no flicker, no manual "emit the initial value" scaffolding.

Hold the `BehaviorSubject` privately and expose it via `.asObservable()`. That way callers can subscribe but cannot call `.next` to mutate.

```ts
import { BehaviorSubject, Observable } from 'rxjs';

interface Counter {
  value: number;
}

const _counter$ = new BehaviorSubject<Counter>({ value: 0 });

// Public, read-only.
export const counter$: Observable<Counter> = _counter$.asObservable();

export function increment(): void {
  const current = _counter$.getValue();
  _counter$.next({ value: current.value + 1 });
}

export function snapshot(): Counter {
  return _counter$.getValue();
}
```

The `Observable<Counter>` return type is not just documentation — TypeScript will reject `counter$.next(...)` at compile time because `.next` is not in the `Observable` surface.

```ts
import { BehaviorSubject, Observable } from 'rxjs';

type ConnectionState = 'connecting' | 'online' | 'offline';

const _connection$ = new BehaviorSubject<ConnectionState>('connecting');

export const connection$: Observable<ConnectionState> =
  _connection$.asObservable();

export function markOnline(): void {
  _connection$.next('online');
}

export function markOffline(): void {
  _connection$.next('offline');
}

export function isOnlineNow(): boolean {
  // `.getValue()` is acceptable for one-shot predicate checks.
  // Don't use it inside a pipeline — it breaks reactivity.
  return _connection$.getValue() === 'online';
}
```

Why `BehaviorSubject` not `Subject`: a React component mounting after the app already went online must paint "online" on first render. A plain `Subject` would hand back nothing until the next state change.

```ts
import { BehaviorSubject, Observable } from 'rxjs';

interface State {
  count: number;
  lastAction: string;
}

type Action =
  | { type: 'inc' }
  | { type: 'dec' }
  | { type: 'reset' };

const initial: State = { count: 0, lastAction: '@@init' };

const _state$ = new BehaviorSubject<State>(initial);
export const state$: Observable<State> = _state$.asObservable();

function reduce(prev: State, action: Action): State {
  switch (action.type) {
    case 'inc':
      return { count: prev.count + 1, lastAction: 'inc' };
    case 'dec':
      return { count: prev.count - 1, lastAction: 'dec' };
    case 'reset':
      return { count: 0, lastAction: 'reset' };
  }
}

export function dispatch(action: Action): void {
  _state$.next(reduce(_state$.getValue(), action));
}

export function getState(): State {
  return _state$.getValue();
}
```

```ts
import { BehaviorSubject, Observable } from 'rxjs';

interface Preferences {
  readonly locale: string;
  readonly timeZone: string;
  readonly emailNotifications: boolean;
}

const defaults: Preferences = {
  locale: 'en-US',
  timeZone: 'UTC',
  emailNotifications: true,
};

const _prefs$ = new BehaviorSubject<Preferences>(defaults);

// Read-only stream: `.asObservable()` strips `.next` from the public type.
export const prefs$: Observable<Preferences> = _prefs$.asObservable();

export function updatePrefs(patch: Partial<Preferences>): void {
  _prefs$.next({ ..._prefs$.getValue(), ...patch });
}

export function currentPrefs(): Preferences {
  return _prefs$.getValue();
}
```

A settings dialog mounted after the user is already logged in instantly renders with the live preferences — no loading flicker.

```ts
import { BehaviorSubject, Observable } from 'rxjs';

interface Toast {
  id: string;
  kind: 'info' | 'warn' | 'error';
  message: string;
}

const _toast$ = new BehaviorSubject<Toast | null>(null);

export const toast$: Observable<Toast | null> = _toast$.asObservable();

export function showToast(t: Toast): void {
  _toast$.next(t);
}

export function dismissToast(): void {
  _toast$.next(null);
}

export function currentToast(): Toast | null {
  return _toast$.getValue();
}
```

`BehaviorSubject` is the right pick over `Subject` because a mid-render `<ToastHost />` component must display the currently visible toast on mount — not miss it because it was fired before subscription.

```ts
import { BehaviorSubject, Observable } from 'rxjs';

interface AuthToken {
  readonly accessToken: string;
  readonly expiresAtMs: number;
}

const _token$ = new BehaviorSubject<AuthToken | null>(null);

export const token$: Observable<AuthToken | null> = _token$.asObservable();

export function setToken(t: AuthToken | null): void {
  _token$.next(t);
}

export function readTokenSync(): AuthToken | null {
  // Valid use of `.getValue()`: HTTP interceptor needs the token synchronously
  // before sending each request. Don't embed it inside a pipeline.
  return _token$.getValue();
}
```

The interceptor grabs the current value synchronously. A React `useAuthToken` hook can `subscribe(token$)` and receive the current value on mount. Both use cases covered by one `BehaviorSubject`.

```ts
import { BehaviorSubject, Observable } from 'rxjs';

type Step = 0 | 1 | 2 | 3;

interface WizardState {
  readonly step: Step;
  readonly dirty: boolean;
}

const initial: WizardState = { step: 0, dirty: false };

const _wizard$ = new BehaviorSubject<WizardState>(initial);

export const wizard$: Observable<WizardState> = _wizard$.asObservable();

export function gotoStep(step: Step): void {
  _wizard$.next({ ..._wizard$.getValue(), step });
}

export function markDirty(): void {
  _wizard$.next({ ..._wizard$.getValue(), dirty: true });
}

export function snapshot(): WizardState {
  return _wizard$.getValue();
}
```

Late-mounted wizard steps see the current step immediately — `BehaviorSubject` replays the last value to new subscribers; `Subject` would not.

`.getValue()` returns the current value synchronously — no subscription, no next-tick. It is fine for one-shot reads at boundaries where you're already leaving the reactive world (form submit handler, HTTP interceptor, imperative adapter). It is NOT fine inside a pipeline — at that point you should be composing operators against the stream, not reaching for imperative state.

```ts
import { BehaviorSubject, Observable } from 'rxjs';

interface Counter {
  count: number;
}

const _c$ = new BehaviorSubject<Counter>({ count: 0 });
export const counter$: Observable<Counter> = _c$.asObservable();

export function tick(): void {
  // OK: imperative tick action, not part of a stream.
  _c$.next({ count: _c$.getValue().count + 1 });
}

export function onSubmit(): number {
  // OK: leaving reactive land, grabbing the snapshot.
  return _c$.getValue().count;
}
```

```ts
import { BehaviorSubject, Observable } from 'rxjs';

interface Tick {
  readonly symbol: string;
  readonly priceUsd: number;
  readonly timestampMs: number;
}

// Seed with a placeholder so subscribers never see "no data".
const seed: Tick = { symbol: 'BTC-USD', priceUsd: 0, timestampMs: 0 };
const _tick$ = new BehaviorSubject<Tick>(seed);

export const tick$: Observable<Tick> = _tick$.asObservable();

export function pushTick(t: Tick): void {
  _tick$.next(t);
}

export function latestTick(): Tick {
  return _tick$.getValue();
}
```

A chart that mounts mid-session immediately renders with `latestTick()` instead of a skeleton. The `Observable<Tick>` public type prevents outside callers from mutating the stream.

```ts
import { BehaviorSubject, Observable } from 'rxjs';

type Locale = 'en' | 'de' | 'fr' | 'ja' | 'zh';

const _locale$ = new BehaviorSubject<Locale>('en');

export const locale$: Observable<Locale> = _locale$.asObservable();

export function setLocale(next: Locale): void {
  if (next === _locale$.getValue()) {
    return; // dedupe — avoid re-emitting the same locale.
  }
  _locale$.next(next);
}

export function currentLocale(): Locale {
  return _locale$.getValue();
}
```

A component that mounts after the user switched to `'de'` receives `'de'` on first render — that's the late-subscriber semantics of `BehaviorSubject`.

```ts
import { BehaviorSubject, Observable } from 'rxjs';

interface Route {
  readonly path: string;
  readonly query: Readonly<Record<string, string>>;
}

const initialRoute: Route = { path: '/', query: {} };

const _route$ = new BehaviorSubject<Route>(initialRoute);

export const route$: Observable<Route> = _route$.asObservable();

export function navigate(r: Route): void {
  _route$.next(r);
}

export function currentRoute(): Route {
  // Synchronous read is the right call for guards / analytics tags
  // that fire imperatively on events.
  return _route$.getValue();
}
